segments.text: with the CIA, just like you cooperated with the Air Force Security Service.
Yeah.
The National Security Agency kind of gave direction to the Air Force Security Service so that everybody was doing something different rather than everybody trying to do the same thing.
Well, what were you doing different here at the National Security Agency
and what you were doing different from the Air Force Security Service?
Well, the Air Force Security Service is gathering intelligence for frontline operation type of thing, whereas the National Security Agency is collecting information on a national level.
I see.
Air Force Security Service products, they went to the National Security Agency.
Okay, now this is during a rather important time in American history.
It was during McCarthyism and the anti-communist
crusade that was going on in America.
The FBI and the CIA, the powers of those two organizations were boosted.
There were loyalty programs in the federal government.
Senator McCarthy himself was making a number of charges against the loyalty of public officials.
Did that have anything to do with your agencies, your jobs?
I don't think so.
No, I don't think so at all.
That was, I would say that had no effect whatsoever.
Okay.
Why didn't, why weren't you assigned to Korea?
Well, see I came back in 48 and
And it just wasn't time for me to rotate again.
See that was what, 52?
See and I just got back from overseas in 48.
And I just got command and security service in 50.
And I guess the job I was doing there was more important than sending me over to be
group commander or wing commander in Korea.
Did you want to go to Korea?
Did you want to go to combat?
Well at that time I had a good job.
While I was at the security service, I was up until 51.
Then the one in Washington was really not a bad job, it was just
just didn't, you had no decision.
You didn't get to make decisions.
No, I mean you really didn't, it was a coordinating type of job.
And that's what my, that's not my cup of tea.
Right.
So why'd you go to an MBA program?
Well, I had a lot of time on my hands.
It was one of these programs that you work 40 hours a week.
And I decided that if I was going to have this kind of job, maybe I would just get a master's degree and get out.
Get out of the service?
Yeah.
At this time, you're thinking about resigning your commission?
Well, you could retire at that time.
So you were beyond your 40, 50, 54.
Oh, you could retire because you just were getting your 20 years in then.
Yeah.
So that's where they got into.
took my master's degree, and I did this at night.
It wasn't on the Air Force paid for part of the tuition and part of the books.
It was a bootstrap program that they had.
Oh, really?
That sounds like a good program.
Yeah, if you were willing to spend your time, the Air Force would pay for about half your expenses of going to school.
So I got my master's degree in November of 54.
And it was real interesting, actually.
The courses I took were real fascinating, really.
It was a two year program.
Yeah, it was about a two year program.
And most of the professors were in
Well, like the Director of Civilian Personnel at the Naval Laboratories, which is an experimental station.
He came in and he ran a course on personnel management.
And then one of the high level
controllers from the Pentagon, ran a controllers course.
So we had real top level professors who actually were not day to day professors.
They were people who were actually on a job, doing it on a day to day basis.
the most boring ones were the professors who had written a book and he would read his book to you.
Oh that's terrible.
And so we complained to him and of course he completely turned it around and worked us to death on making special assignments to each one of us where we had to read
some book and give a book review on it as to what it said, almost every week.
When we complained to him about it, we wanted to get more out of it than just reading his book on industrial management.
He really gave it to us.
Well, it sounds like you weren't, after 18 years in the service, you weren't very
happy with your job in Washington D.C. and you were thinking about alternatives at that time.

Well, I figured that at that time I was looking for a promotion and I was looking for a job to get promoted and if you weren't going to promote me I just didn't want to hang around and be dead wood in the Air Force.
And I see, I saw no future in that.
So, I was really willing to try my hand at something else.
And then what happened?
What happened from 1953 to 1955?
You got your master's degree, but you ended your duty with the National Security Agency.
54, and then I went to the National War College in 54.
Okay, let's talk about the National War College.
How did that differ from the Air Force War College?
Well, the National War College is a real high level college and this is where you get into political strengths of Russia and China.

and you had people like Ball and to give you, oh yeah, you had really high level State Department people, Secretary of State, Secretary of Defense, all these type of individuals were over there talking to you about
and this is more of a geo, I said geo- International relations?
International relations type of thing.
And we took a trip and we went to London, England and was briefed by
not only the State Department and the ambassador over there, but his counterpart would brief us.
We went to Spain, we had the same thing.
We went to Italy, had the same thing.
We went to Libya, we had the same thing.
We went to Vienna, and we had the same thing.
And back to Paris, and you get briefings on the economic status of the
of France, the political status of the state of France, the military status of France, and you had, it was quite an impressive course.
And again, it was a seminar type of thing, and you had to prepare various papers on

they would assign you some kind of a subject, or you could choose a subject, say, from 10 various items they'd give you, and then you would have to read up and prepare a master's type thesis on that particular subject.
And like your critical metals,
strategic metals type of sources and what happens if Russia takes over South Africa or why.
What are you going to do?
That type of situations.
That sounds fascinating.
Quite a change from the Air War College where it was much more toward personal management.
This one seems much more toward international relations.
World strategy.
It prepares you, yeah, prepares you for I would say jobs on the Joint Chiefs of Staff and exchange student exchanges for in the State Department.
And you had, well let's see, you had a high-level senior ambassador as one of the directors who worked permanently over there.
And you had a
commandant who was normally an Air Force or an Army or a Navy three-star general.
And then you had a deputy from each of the other two services plus the State Department.
And then you had
about a third of the students or a fourth of the students were from the State Department, who were future ambassadors.
No kidding.
Oh yeah, so you had a lot of high level people there.
Sounds like your students would be really stimulating too.
Oh yeah, you know you had, no I enjoyed it, I enjoyed it.
I see I was assigned to the, in 58 I was assigned to Ambassador MacArthur's, now he's nephew I think of Jim MacArthur.
He was the ambassador to Japan and I was the Air Force, I was in the military assistance group.
Air Force.
That's a horrible job too.
We'll get to that, but I want to stay here at the National War College.
It sounds like a very stimulating assignment.
Is this one year?
One year now.
I graduated what about June.
Sounds like an elite job too.
I mean an elite position.
Sounds like they were, is it would it be true to say that people go to the National War College they're grooming for generalships?
Yeah, in fact
I don't know what percentage it is, but I would say probably 70% of the graduates of the National War College make general officer, flag officer.
Well, if you select the cream of your crop to go there, well, it's natural that you should be in line for promotion.
In the future.
You were probably really delighted then when you got this assignment.
Oh, yeah.
Not only did you.
not only to get away from the deputy directorship, but also... Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Opens up a new assignment for you.
And then, then from, no, I would say that that was, both Air War College is a very stimulating school, and the National War College, I would say, is very stimulating.
In fact, I think any education is stimulating.
Sure.
If you are
I think going and getting my master's degree was very stimulating.

Do you think the fact that you went ahead on your own time and received that master's degree, do you think that had anything, and demonstrated to the Air Force that you had an interest in higher education, do you think that had anything to do with the fact that you were appointed to the National War College?
No, because I didn't get my master's degree, I wasn't awarded my master's degree until November after I entered there in September.
But still, you were going.
I was going, but I don't know that anybody knew about it.
Oh, I see.
Although, see, you're just not a student.
If you're going under bootstrap, all you do is sign the papers over at the university and they submit them to the Air Force for payment.
It was after the National War College that you got your own command.
379th Wing in Homestead, Florida.
Can you tell me about that?
Well see, General LeMay was Commander Sack at the time.
Right.
And General LeMay was, I knew him from Hawaii.
When I first was assigned to Hawaii as second lieutenant, he ran a navigation school over there, so as a first lieutenant, so
My name was familiar to him and I guess he asked for me.
Oh really?
Well I don't know how I got his sign, but anyway I got his sign to Lake Charles, Louisiana and then I got 379th Bomb Wing because that 379th Bomb Wing was being activated at the time.
Okay.
These, what type of bombers?
Yeah.
And how many did you have, and tell me about the size of the unit, and your aim, your mission?
Well, the 79th had three squadrons of B-47s, then I had a squadron of KC-97s, who were tankers.
And
Actually, the command must have been about 1500 people.
And we moved down to Homestead and we opened up Homestead as an air base.
So you opened up and built another one?
Oh yeah, I mean that's... That's one of the, seems like that's one of the themes running throughout your entire career is that you're opening up and building bases.
That's what my wife says every time I
Every time I get it built up while somebody else takes over.
Well that seems like the Air Force was quite happy with your job doing that.
Well we did a pretty good job on 379th and Brown Wing.
I was real proud of 379th because we had a former cadre out of Lake Charles and then we, the few people that I had, we went up to Waco and selected all our pilots.
for our B-47s to be trained.

They were going through a flying school up at John Connolly Air Force Base at Waco and we had one accident during the entire activation period and that was right at the last where we had sent in a few
fill a cruise that we didn't have a chance to select and then one of them had an accident.
So we had it pretty well organized and it's I think the first time that we'd gone through an activation program of B-47s that we had had only one accident.
In each quadrant of B-47s are there 15?
Yeah, there was about 15 of these squads, so we had 45.
Yeah, it was a pretty good outfit.
You had about 45 B-47s and about 15 tankers?
About 15, 18 tankers, yeah.
And where were these B-47s?
Here you are down in Florida.
Where was your primary flight area?
What did you take care of, the Caribbean?
No, you were just prepared to move to a foreign base.

And then from there you could, I don't know what the strategy was, whether or not you were outside the range of the Russian missiles, and that you take off from there and be refueled a couple of times, one in northern United States, one over Newfoundland, so that you could accomplish your mission.
At that time I think the strategy was that you either move the wing forward to North Africa or some other, lowering the main, or just take off from there and be refueled.
And after that, I think they changed the strategy so that you don't have a whole wing of airplanes on one base.
They were going to scatter them around so you have one squadron at a base so that they're not so easily destroyed.
But that was real, yeah, in fact I enjoyed that job too.
I think that you would.
How many pilots did you have then if you had 60 planes under you?

Well you probably had around 36 pilots or 40 pilots per squadron and then you had oh let's say 30 in the air in the wing headquarters and see one of your programs was you'd deploy from Homestead over to over to
to North Africa, just south of Gibraltar.
And so we would get refueled over the Azores and refueled over Newfoundland and either back to the States, or if you're going that way you get refueled twice going.
And that was just a test of your capability of deploying rapidly overseas.
And I would imagine that you partook in a number of these missions.
Oh yeah, yeah.
In fact we were at one time coming back from one of those missions, I was hooked onto a tanker and it developed engine trouble in the Azores and it ditched.
It did?
And we went down and circled it until the RC Rescue got there.
Has anybody hurt?
No, I don't think anyone.
Those tankers float real good and apparently the pilot did a real good job of setting it down in water.
And then coming back, see we were on our way back and that put us about 45 minutes behind the flow of airplanes and so when we got over
over New England, we were getting intercepted because we weren't on the flight plan, see, because we were behind schedule.
And about an hour behind schedule, but we finally arrived back at Homestead without landing.
And when we got to Newfoundland, of course all the tankers were just about headed home, so we were screaming for tankers for fuel.
and some tanker commander said, where are you?
We don't know where we are.
They weren't in the holding pattern where they were supposed to be.
They were on their way home.
He said, I see a contrail.
He said, make a nine degree turn to the left.
We made a nine degree turn to the left.
Then he directed us into him, we got fueled, and we did that at Harman in Newfoundland, and then we came on home.
But it was exciting, I guess.
I betcha, I betcha.
You know, this is SAC in the 1950s was considered America's first line of offense.
Oh, I tell you, SAC
LeMay is a wonderful guy.
I mean he is nothing, there's no commander like him, never like him.
I mean he built SAC up until he was really a professional out there, but he was very very brutal as far as firing people is concerned.
I mean you either were a lucky commander or if you were unlucky why you didn't want an unlucky commander around.
I mean, maybe it wasn't your fault at all that you had a bunch of accidents, but he said, well, you're just unlucky.
You're just tough.
I mean, it's just too bad.
And that's when I was...
So he'd fire men because of that?
Oh, yeah.
Even if they didn't have anything to do with it?
Well, he used to clean out the wing commander, the director of operations, the director of maintenance.
He was just completely replaced with the top four people in the wing.
Overnight.
You have a couple of airplanes run together, lose a lot of people, why?
He says, I can't afford it.
So he kept everybody nervous.
He kept everybody nervous.
He came down, remember one time he came down to inspect the 379th, probably down there,
and I showed him around and spent a couple hours showing him the wing and what we were doing and briefed him on flying time and pilot efficiency and all that type of thing.
And then I took him up and delivered him to Arthur Godfrey.
He was a very, very close friend of Arthur Godfrey's up in Miami.
Oh, he was?
Oh, yeah.
And he was going out on a fishing trip with Arthur Godfrey
And when I got back to base, my guy said, what happened?
How did he like it?
And I said, well, I don't know how he liked it.
And I said, the only thing I know is I'm still his wing commander, because he introduced me to Arthur Godfrey as his wing commander.
So I knew I still had a job.
But was that tenuous?
It was that tenuous, Curtis LeMay?
Working with him?
I mean, you didn't know from one minute to the next that you were still going to be a... No, well, it wasn't really, it really wasn't that.
He just wasn't, he wasn't a guy that would brag on you.
You know, he wouldn't say, well, boy, that's a good job, or you look like you're in good shape.
He just expects it.
Yeah, he just expected it.
And I said the only thing he did was he just grunted now and then, but
I said to him, after I got to Arthur Godfrey, he introduced me as wing commander, so I knew I still had a job.
So I was kidding, I guess.
What kind of man was LeMay?
Did you get an opportunity to really find out what he was like besides off the job sort of?
Well, I think LeMay is a workaholic.
I think his job is his job.
And Mrs. LeMay
He was an individual who was very conscious of his people and taking care of his people.
And he had a family, he organized the family services in Sac.
It was second to none.
That when an outfit went TDY, why the officers and wives who were left, who stayed at home would take care of the wives who were
the pilots and the crews that were overseas, and they really took care of them.
I mean, they would be sure that none of them had any problems.
And when you reported in, you could go to Family Services and draw beds and sheets, and they had a fully equipped program.
And when somebody got killed,
in an aircraft accident why he wanted to be sure that that wife was taken care of.
And she was given all the assistance and even after a year after that she still was looked after to be sure that the Air Force hadn't forgotten her.
I mean, he's well, I was in the hospital out at Wilford Hall here about
away six or eight months ago.
I was his roommate.
He was in the urology ward and I was over his eye.
You mean he was here six or eight months ago?
Yeah.
Oh yeah.
I thought he was out in California.
Well he is in California but he was flown back here for operation.
And you were his roommate?
I was his roommate and he had had his operation about three or four days before mine.
So he's always bringing me water.
Really?
Yeah.
I mean, he's that type of guy.
And he would tell the doctor, he says, now, he says, Doc, blah, blah, this is a friend of mine now.
This is Tex Adler.
I want you to take care of him.
When he left.
I mean, he's that type of an individual.
But as far as professionalism is concerned, he expects you to be the best.
And he certainly didn't expect you to slough off anything.
He expects you to work 24 hours a day if necessary to get the job done.
It's just like in the navigation school in Hawaii.
That's the first time I'd run into him.
You have a navigation flight of 200 miles over water.
Being a mile off wasn't good enough.
He wants you to be right on the button.
If you were happy.
